{
  "insight": "- The clustering reveals a strong tendency for methods to group based on their planning approach and object configuration, such as the \"Grasp evaluation + Sampler / Two-finger / Singulated\" group (10 methods) which focuses on generating and evaluating multiple grasp candidates for isolated objects, often using point clouds and overhead views. This indicates a preference for thorough exploration and evaluation in simpler, singulated scenarios.\n- In the \"Reinforcement learning / Two-finger / Singulated\" group (14 methods), methods like Dex-Net and GA-DDPG are clustered together due to their reliance on reinforcement learning to learn grasp policies from simulation data. These methods typically use overhead or eye-in-hand cameras and focus on two-finger grippers, highlighting the effectiveness of RL in optimizing grasp success rates for isolated objects.\n- The \"Sampling / Two-finger / Piled\" group (9 methods) includes methods like GPD and VGN, which are designed to handle more complex, piled object configurations. These methods often use point clouds and eye-in-hand cameras, emphasizing the need for robust sampling and evaluation techniques to deal with occlusions and inter-object contacts.\n- The \"Direct regression / Two-finger / Structured\" group (6 methods) consists of approaches like Contact-GraspNet and ICG-Net, which directly predict grasp poses from structured object arrangements. These methods frequently use point clouds and oblique views, indicating a focus on leveraging geometric and structural information to achieve high grasp success rates in organized settings.\n- The \"Sampling / Three-finger / Singulated\" group (4 methods) includes DDG and Multi-FinGAN, which are tailored for dexterous three-finger grippers and singulated objects. These methods often use RGBD images and oblique views, reflecting the need for detailed visual and geometric information to plan complex, multi-finger grasps.\n- The \"Sampling / Two-finger / Singulated\" group (6 methods) includes GraspMolmo, 6-DoF GraspNet, and GCNGrasp, which use sampling-based planning with two-finger grippers for isolated objects. This group is distinguished by its use of point cloud inputs and simulation-based training, with methods like GraspMolmo incorporating natural language grounding and GCNGrasp leveraging graph convolutional networks for task-oriented grasping.\n- The \"Direct regression / Two-finger / Singulated\" group (7 methods) features methods like 3DAPNet and GPNet, which predict grasp poses directly from sensor data for isolated objects. These methods commonly use point clouds and overhead views, suggesting a streamlined approach to grasp planning that balances simplicity and efficiency.",
